Freight transportation is the physical process of transporting commodities or merchandise from one place to another for a fee.â source

# Function for reading in CSVs
read <- function(year) {
  file_name <- paste0("flights", year, ".csv") 
  file_path <- here("data", file_name) 
  
  # Read and filter dataset
  df <- read.csv(file_path) %>%
    filter(FREIGHT != 0) %>% 
    clean_names()
  
  return(df)
}

Data editing for the map

Create DF with Freight_all and airport coordinates

Sorting out the iatas

I have been planning to use the airportr package to be able to get the coordinates for each airport for the map I want to make. I realized after looking at the freight data that there were world codes but no variable for the iata. After examining the data, I learned the iatas were just the âoriginâ and âdestâ columns.

Code 
# Rename origin and dest columns
freight_all <- freight_all %>% 
  rename(iata_origin = origin) %>% 
  rename(iata_dest = dest)

I will also need to create columns in the air_coords data that will have the same names as the columns in the freight_all dataframe

Code 
# Duplicating iata coloumn
air_coords$iata_origin = air_coords$iata

# Renaming original iata column
air_coords_rn <- air_coords %>% 
  rename(iata_dest = iata)

Adding coordinates to both the destination airports and the origin airports

Up until now, most of my work on dataframes with coordinates only had one set of coordinates per row, but in this case I will need there to be two. To start this process, I need to take the air_coords data and duplicate the lat-longs so that there is one for the destination, and one for the origin. I am a bit concerned here because I do not know if it matters if the lat longs are not called latitude/longitude

Code 
# Duplicate and rename lat longs
air_coords_rn$lat_dest = air_coords_rn$latitude
air_coords_rn$long_dest = air_coords_rn$longitude

Then I will rename the original lat longs

Code 
# Rename original lat longs
air_duocoords <- air_coords_rn %>% 
  rename(lat_origin = latitude) %>% 
  rename(long_origin = longitude)

Joining the data

The first time I did this, it was with a full join which resulted in a lot of NAs, but then I used the left join and just joined the twice to ensure that the data had the coords matched for both dest and orign. To double check they were correct, I went through and manually checked a couple flights to see if they were correct and they were!

Code 
# Join freight_all with air_duocoords to get destination coordinates
freight_coords <- freight_all %>%
  left_join(air_duocoords %>%
              select(iata_dest, lat_dest, long_dest), 
            by = "iata_dest") %>%
  # Join again to get origin coordinates
  left_join(air_duocoords %>%
              select(iata_origin, lat_origin, long_origin), 
            by = "iata_origin")

airport_routes <- freight_coords %>%
  group_by(iata_origin, iata_dest) %>%
  mutate(freight_shipped = sum(freight, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%  # Sum freight shipped for each route
  ungroup() %>%  # Remove grouping after adding the freight count
  distinct(iata_origin, iata_dest, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%  # Keep only unique routes
  arrange(desc(freight_shipped))

Making the map

Code 
# Custom function to plot connections for your data
plot_my_connection <- function(dep_lon, dep_lat, arr_lon, arr_lat, ...) {
  
  # Get intermediate points between origin and destination
  inter <- gcIntermediate(c(dep_lon, dep_lat), c(arr_lon, arr_lat), n=50, addStartEnd=TRUE, breakAtDateLine=FALSE)
  inter <- data.frame(inter)
  
  # Check if the route crosses the date line (180 degrees longitude)
  diff_of_lon = abs(dep_lon) + abs(arr_lon)
  
  # Plot lines accordingly based on whether it crosses the date line or not
  if(diff_of_lon > 180){
    # Split the line into two parts and plot each separately
    lines(subset(inter, lon >= 0), ...)
    lines(subset(inter, lon < 0), ...)
  } else {
    # Plot the whole line as a single segment
    lines(inter, ...)
  }
}
Code 
# Example: Plotting the map with top_20_routes data
par(mar = c(0, 0, 0, 0))  # Set margin to zero
map('world', col = "#f2f2f2", fill = TRUE, bg = "white", lwd = 0.05, mar = rep(0, 4), border = 0, ylim = c(-80, 80))

# Plot lines connecting each pair of origin and destination
for(i in 1:nrow(top_20_routes)) {
  plot_my_connection(
    dep_lon = top_20_routes$long_origin[i],
    dep_lat = top_20_routes$lat_origin[i],
    arr_lon = top_20_routes$long_dest[i],
    arr_lat = top_20_routes$lat_dest[i],
    col = "skyblue",  # Line color
    lwd = 1  # Line width
  )
}

# Add points for origin airports
points(x = top_20_routes$long_origin, y = top_20_routes$lat_origin, col = "slateblue", cex = 1, pch = 20)

# Add points for destination airports
points(x = top_20_routes$long_dest, y = top_20_routes$lat_dest, col = "red", cex = 1, pch = 20)

Code 
# Function to create the route map
plot_routes_ggplot <- function(routes_data) {
  
  # Get world map data
  world_map <- map_data("world")
  
  # Create ggplot object
  map_pounds <- ggplot() +
    # Add world map background
    geom_polygon(data = world_map, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group),
                 fill = "#f2f2f2", color = "white") +
    
    # Add curved lines for routes
    geom_curve(data = routes_data, 
               aes(x = long_origin, y = lat_origin, 
                   xend = long_dest, yend = lat_dest),
               curvature = 0.2, color = "skyblue", size = 0.5) +
    
    # Add points for origin airports
    geom_point(data = routes_data, aes(x = long_origin, y = lat_origin), 
               color = "slateblue", size = 2) +
    
    # Add points for destination airports
    geom_point(data = routes_data, aes(x = long_dest, y = lat_dest), 
               color = "red", size = 2) +
    
    # Theme settings
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(axis.text = element_blank(),
          axis.ticks = element_blank(),
          panel.grid = element_blank()) +
    labs(title = "Top Air Freight Routes", x = "", y = "")
  
  return(map_pounds)
}

# Store the plot in a variable
route_map <- plot_routes_ggplot(top_20_routes)

# Display the plot
print(route_map)

freight_month <- freight_all %>%
  group_by(year, month) %>%
  summarise(total_freight = sum(freight, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop") %>%
  mutate(date = make_date(year, month, 1))

timeline <-

Create base plot

Code 
plot_base <- ggplot() +
  
  # Add labels, subtitles, and caption to plot
  labs(
    title = "Airplanes & Freight",
    subtitle = "Airplanes carry a lot of freight different places",
    caption = "they can flY!"
    ) +
  
  # apply a completely empty theme ----
  theme_void() +
  
  # further customize theme ----
  theme(
    
   # Set preferences for text including font and size
    text = element_text(size = 16, 
                        lineheight = 0.3, 
                        color = "black"),
    
    # Fill in the background with color
    
    # make plot background black
    plot.background = element_rect(fill = "lightblue1", 
                                   color = "lightblue1"),
    
    # Plot the title and add text preferences
    plot.title = element_text(size = 42, 
                              face = "bold", 
                              hjust = 0.5, 
                              margin = margin(b = 10)),
    
    # Plot subtitle and add text preferences
    plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5, 
                                 margin = margin(b = 20)),
    
    # format plot caption using {ggtext} to render fontawesome icons ----
    plot.caption = ggtext::element_markdown(face = "italic",
                                            color = "white",
                                            hjust = 0.5,
                                            margin = margin(t = 20)),

    # Add margins and space to the plot
    plot.margin = margin(b = 20, t = 50, r = 50, l = 50)
    
  )
